pr_review_comment_body:
> Here you check type twice. Once in `is_convertible` and another in `convert`. Why not using only `convert` and return nullptr when it fail?

I agree with the problem of the double check. But Your option would
imply either unnecessary conversions, or convoluted code, as in:

```
// we want to try two functions : f(set<int>, set<int>) or f (list<int>, list<int>)

if(set<int> arg0 = try_convert<set<int>>(py_arg0)) {
    if(set<int> arg1 = try_convert<set<int>>(py_arg1)) {
        return f0(arg0, arg1);
    }
    // arg0 will be destroyed here, so that's a potentially very costly
    // conversion that proved to be useless
}
else if (list<int> arg0 = try_convert<list<int>>(py_arg0)) {
    if(list<int> arg1 = try_convert<list<int>>(py_arg1)) {
        return f1(arg0, arg1);
    }  
    // arg0 will be destroyed here too
}
```

@jakubhava The problem here is that we cannot shadow jetty without processing H2O dependencies. That would mean to include h2o dependencies and i would like to avoid that. 

But worth experimenting - we can include only shaddowed jetty and processed h2o-core, but we need to make sure, the we publish dependencies in POM correctly.

@tomkraljevic the problem is more complex. In the context of Spark package, there is no actual binary which you can put on `-cp` as it is mentioned in documentation.  There is only a reference to a package. However, users can do that with binary distribution from download page (we need to put it into SW documentation).

Furthermore, so far it looks like people mostly using automatic mode (equivalent of `-internal_security_enabled` in Hadoop).

@scottpurdy:
> Why shout-case?

It stands out when looking through build output. Don't mind changing. Let me know.

I'd probably do something like:
```
def _section_radial_distances(..., iterator_type):
    ...

def section_term_radial_distances(...):
    return _section_radial_distances(..., iterator_type=Tree.ileaf)

def section_bif_radial_distances(...):
    return _section_radial_distances(..., iterator_type=Tree.ibifurcation_point)
```

This way it's apparent where the bulk of the algorithm is, and how the two functions differ

Just an idea. What about doing something like this:
In a file named `contrib/records_utils.py`
```python
def index_record_modification_factory(record_to_index_and_type):
  def index_record_modification(sender, changes):
      ...
      for obj, change in changes:
          if isinstance(obj, RecordMetadata):
              index, doc_type = record_to_index_and_type(record, index_default, doc_type_default)
    ...
    return index_record_modification

def record_to_index_and_type(record, index_default, doc_type_default):
    schema = record.json.get('$schema')
             if isinstance(schema, dict):
                 schema = schema.get('$ref')
             if schema:
                 index, doc_type = schema_to_index(
                     schema, index_names=index_names
                 )
```
In file `contrib/records.py`
```
models_committed.connect(index_record_modification_factory(record_to_index_and_type))
```

That way, if index or object type names can be decided otherwise and the indexer can still be used.

